The low biosafety awareness and practices in the country are having negative effects on health care, agriculture, environment and other sectors of the country. Experts under the aegis of the Nigerian Biological Safety Association (NiBSA) made the disclosure in a statement signed by the association’s spokesman, Jack Lampang Abia (Jnr), yesterday in Abuja. The association said humans, animals, forests, scientists, researchers, and even the climate were also bearing the brunt of the poor knowledge and practices, adding that the fragility of communities to new bio-risk was worrisome not only to researchers but the entire global science community. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY Biosafety, also known as biosecurity, involves safety measures to prevent personal, laboratory and environmental exposure to potentially infectious agents or biohazards.  ‘Why Nigeria lags behind in biosecurity, biosafety programmes’ Govt agencies, institutions to assist Biosafety agency regulate GMOs What they do not tell you  about Genetic Modification (III)